In React, the event type used to handle form submissions to prevent the default behavior (such as page reload) is ` onSubmit `.

To prevent the default form submission behavior (e.g., reloading the page or submitting the form data to the server), you can use the event object's `.preventDefault()` method within the event handler function. Here's an example:

```jsx
import React from 'react';

function MyForm() {
  const handleSubmit = (event) => {
    event.preventDefault(); // Prevent the default form submission behavior

    // Add your custom logic here

    console.log('Form submitted');
  };

  return (
    <form onSubmit={handleSubmit}>
      <label>
        Name:
        <input type="text" name="name" />
      </label>
      <input type="submit" value="Submit" />
    </form>
  );
}

export default MyForm;
```

In this example, `handleSubmit` is called when the form is submitted. The `event.preventDefault()` call stops the form from performing its default action (submission), and the form submission is handled by your custom logic instead.

MATLAB does not have a built-in function specifically named for a "high-order synchrosqueezing transform," but you can use the `synchrosqueezing` function from the Wavelet Toolbox for synchrosqueezing based time-frequency analysis. For a high-order synchrosqueezing transform, you might need to implement a custom solution or use a combination of functions.

However, if you want to perform synchrosqueezing transform on an ECG signal, you can use the `wsst` (Wavelet Synchrosqueezed Transform) function which is also available in the Wavelet Toolbox. The `wsst` function can be used to get the synchrosqueezed transform of your signal.

Here is an example of how you might use the `wsst` function:

```matlab
% Load your noisy ECG signal
% Assuming you have a time vector t and signal x
loadNoisyECG(); % You need to define or load your data
[nx, nt] = size(x);

% Perform wavelet synchrosqueezed transform
[S, F, T] = wsst(x);

% Plot the synchrosqueezed transform
imagesc(T, F, abs(S));
xlabel('Time');
ylabel('Frequency');
title('Synchrosqueezed Transform');
colorbar;
```

For more advanced/high-order functionality, you might need to refer to specialized toolboxes or implement custom code based on research papers that describe high-order synchrosqueezing transforms. 

If you don't have the Wavelet Toolbox, you can still perform synchrosqueezing using other libraries or implement the algorithm yourself following the original synchrosqueezing transform papers. 

For specific high-order synchrosqueezing, consider implementing or using the `hssque` function which is part of the "Synchrosqueezing Toolbox" provided by École Polytechnique Fédérale de Lausanne (EPFL) and available on MATLAB File Exchange or other academic resources.

Here is an example using `hssque`:

```matlab
% Load your noisy ECG signal
loadNoisyECG(); % You need to define or load your data

% Perform high-order synchrosqueezing transform
[S, F, T] = hssque(x, fs); % fs is the sampling frequency

% Plot the high-order synchrosqueezed transform
imagesc(T, F, abs(S));
xlabel('Time');
ylabel('Frequency');
title('High-Order Synchrosqueezed Transform');
colorbar;
```

Ensure that you have the correct toolbox or custom implementation available for `hssque` or a similar function.

