In ActionScript 3, if you want to handle component layout logic after it has been added to the display list (i.e., after it has been added to the stage), you should listen for the `ADDED_TO_STAGE` event.

Here’s how you can set it up:

```as3
import flash.display.DisplayObjectContainer;
import flash.events.Event;

var component:DisplayObjectContainer = new DisplayObjectContainer();

// Listen for the ADDED_TO_STAGE event
component.addEventListener(Event.ADDED_TO_STAGE, onAddedToStage);

// Add the component to the stage or another DisplayObjectContainer
addChild(component);

// Event handler for the ADDED_TO_STAGE event
function onAddedToStage(event:Event):void {
    // The component has been added to the stage.
    // Now you can handle your layout logic here.

    // Example: Initialize layout
    layoutComponent();

    // Remove the listener since it's only needed once
    event.target.removeEventListener(Event.ADDED_TO_STAGE, onAddedToStage);
}

function layoutComponent():void {
    // Put your layout logic here
    // For example, positioning, sizing, or applying any styles.
}
```

In this example, the `layoutComponent` function will only be called after the component has been added to the stage. By removing the listener after the event handler is called, you ensure that the event listener does not remain attached indefinitely, which can be important for performance, especially if the component is reused or exists for a long time.

Alternatively, if you are sure the component will only be added once and don't want to remove the listener, you can keep it attached, but it's generally cleaner to remove it for better programming practice.

In CSS, the property used to control the space between a flex container's lines along the cross axis when items wrap is `gap` (or `row-gap`/`column-gap` in older versions of CSS before the introduction of `gap` for flex and grid layouts).

For flex layouts, you can use `gap` to control the space between flex items both along the main axis and the cross axis if the items wrap. 

However, if you specifically want to control the space between lines along the cross axis (i.e., the vertical space between rows if the items are wrapping horizontally), you can use `row-gap` (or `column-gap` if the items are wrapping vertically).

Example:
```css
.flex-container {
  display: flex;
  flex-wrap: wrap;
  row-gap: 10px; /* This controls the space between lines along the cross axis */
}
```

In modern CSS, it's recommended to use `gap` for simplicity:
```css
.flex-container {
  display: flex;
  flex-wrap: wrap;
  gap: 10px; /* This controls the space between items both along the main and cross axes */
}
```

So, the property you're looking for to control the space between lines along the cross axis specifically is `row-gap` (or `gap` if you want to control both directions).

