To enable vertical scrolling inside a specific element when the content overflows, you can use the `overflow-y` CSS property and set it to `auto`. Alternatively, you can use the `overflow` property and set it to `auto` or `scroll`, depending on your needs.

Here's a quick explanation of each:

1. **Using `overflow-y`:**
   ```css
   element {
       overflow-y: auto;
   }
   ```
   This will add a vertical scrollbar only when it's needed.

2. **Using `overflow`:**
   ```css
   element {
       overflow: auto;
   }
   ```
   This can add both vertical and horizontal scrollbars if the content overflows in either direction, but will only show what is necessary.

If you only want vertical scrolling and ensure that horizontal scrolling is disabled, you can be more specific:
```css
element {
   overflow-y: auto;
   overflow-x: hidden;
}
```

Here's a complete example:
```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Scrollable Box</title>
    <style>
        .scrollable-container {
            width: 300px;
            height: 200px;
            border: 1px solid #000;
            overflow-y: auto; /* or overflow: auto; */
        }

        .content {
            height: 500px;
            background-color: lightblue;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div class="scrollable-container">
